{"id":"1802.02302","submitter":"Eugene Feinberg","authors":"Eugene A. Feinberg, Pavlo O. Kasyanov, Michael Z. Zgurovsky","title":"An example showing that A-lower semi-continuity is essential for minimax\n  continuity theorems","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Recently Feinberg et al. [arXiv:1609.03990] established results on continuity\nproperties of minimax values and solution sets for a function of two variables\ndepending on a parameter. Such minimax problems appear in games with perfect\ninformation, when the second player knows the move of the first one, in\nturn-based games, and in robust optimization. Some of the results in\n[arXiv:1609.03990] are proved under the assumption that the multifunction,\ndefining the domains of the second variable, is $A$-lower semi-continuous. The\n$A$-lower semi-continuity property is stronger than lower semi-continuity, but\nin several important cases these properties coincide. This note provides an\nexample demonstrating that in general the $A$-lower semi-continuity assumption\ncannot be relaxed to lower semi-continuity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 7 Feb 2018 04:20:27 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 10 Feb 2018 20:52:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-02-13"}
